ey are alone in th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">e circumstances which have led to them leaving the academia or STEM career. I am glad to see that the statistics are now out to indicate that there is a problem and a trend.  Also I am pleased to see that there is some interest in the authorities to do som</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ething about it. </span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Why do numbers of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps"> </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I believe there are several reasons behind this matter as follows:</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">1- Lack of equal opportunity for women in assessment of promotion:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I think women </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">are not favoured in terms of promotion. If the record were to be taken out carefully which normally does not happen at</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">university, it would have become clear that with equal CV, majority of women tend to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hold by far</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lower grades, position and salary. Altho</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ugh in most systems there seems to be a supposedly appeal</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">system of scrutinising this, I believe women are less likely to use the system. They are generally more accepting of the system and tend not to challenge the decisions. So they get beaten by general</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ly more accepting and less challenging nature. Also it is possible that the male dominated culture in STEM does not help this.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The only way to avoid the discrimination is by setting more rigour system of scrutinising it.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There is a huge gap between women’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and men’s salary in academia and if you question this they will say the role/job description is different. Whilst you are fully aware that your job demand and description has been exactly the same as your male colleague next door. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2- Many female academi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cs might lose their interest in career progress as later in life they have children</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This is because</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> still mothers are known to be the centre of the family and care at home.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Their priority somehow changes towards their family and motherhood role and their </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">career becomes a secondary focus. The current academic progression demand does which requires </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">longer hours at work do</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> not tolerate this change of focus.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3- In many families still the income of the women is considered as second income and not the main incom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for the family.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">herefore women are more likely to give up work in cases that for example moving of the family needs to happen. Women become the followers rather than the leaders in these situations.  </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">When women leave academia, what careers do they transition into? </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I have seen some go to industry as it allows them to have a more balanced life/work role. The demand of academic work does not allow for this balance easily</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Some choose to become housewife </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">or pick up much less demanding work on part time basis. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women graduates and PhD students in academic careers?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There could be several ways to retain women graduates or PhD students:</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">1-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Bringing to light and introducing successful women in STEM as example to the graduates and PhD candidates. The more successful women are seen in STEM, the more female graduates are encouraged to stay in.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2-Of course if we want more successful women in ST</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">EM to show as example, then we need to work on changing the culture </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> this success</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to become possible</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Providing awareness to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">management who make</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> decision in terms of progression of staff is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">essential. System of scrutiny of management in this matter</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> would help. For example setting one of the measures of evaluation of the university on the basis of provision of good environment for female academics to grow</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">could be quite helpful. If STEM related departments at university are obliged to provide statis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tics on what happens to their female staff they would have to act fairly in terms of opportunities they provide. The system of scrutiny does not exist at the moment. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3- Special funding scheme to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">especially encourage female graduates and PhD students to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">stay in Academia. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers? </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I think government</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">/higher education</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> could help in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">what is mentioned in my previous answer.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">1- Reinforcing system of scrutinising </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">women progression in STEM:</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Setting one of the measures of evaluation of the university on the basis of provision of good environment for female academics to grow could be quite helpful. If STEM related departments at university are obliged to provide stati</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">stics on what happens to their female staff they would have to act fairly in terms of opportunities they provide. The system of scrutiny does not exist at the moment. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Provision of special funding for attracting more women</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to STEM and also working on ch</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ange of culture from "all men in trousers in STEM to a mixed culture".</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3- Some systems such as US they support spouse recruitment system. This does not exist in UK. I suppose the government could bring such policies in place. For example in the cases of tw</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">o academics in the family at the moment it is very difficult for husband</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and wife both</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to find job</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in the same place and therefore they have to either live separate or one (normally wife) to give up </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">her</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> job. These policies could help to retain the women i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n academia whilst they stay with their family. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>